# Java Coding Standards

## Lombok Usage

Use Lombok wherever possible to eliminate boilerplate. Lombok is configured in the parent POM
via `maven-compiler-plugin` annotation processor paths (version 1.18.38).

### DTOs / Request / Response classes

Always annotate with: `@Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor @AllArgsConstructor @Builder`

```java
@Getter
@Setter
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
@Builder
public class SignupResponse {
    private Long userId;
    private String email;
}
```

Always build DTOs using the builder pattern:

```java
// GOOD
SignupResponse.builder()
    .userId(userId)
    .email(email)
    .build();

// BAD — never use constructor directly for DTOs
new SignupResponse(userId, email);
```

### Entities (JPA)

Do **not** use `@Builder` or `@AllArgsConstructor` on JPA entities. Entities manage their own
state with explicit constructors, targeted setters, and domain methods. Use `@Getter` only for
read accessors; write only the setters that make domain sense (e.g. `setVerified`, not a blanket
`@Setter`). JPA requires a protected no-arg constructor.

```java
@Entity
public class AuthUser {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    protected AuthUser() {}               // JPA
    public AuthUser(String email, String passwordHash, Role role) { ... }
    // explicit getters, targeted setters, domain methods
}
```

### Services / Controllers / Config

Use constructor injection. Let Spring autowire via the single constructor — no `@Autowired` needed.

```java
@Service
public class AuthService {
    private final AuthUserRepository repo;
    public AuthService(AuthUserRepository repo) { this.repo = repo; }
}
```

## Dependency Injection

- Prefer **constructor injection** over field injection (`@Autowired` on fields).
- All injected fields must be `private final`.
- If a class has a single constructor, omit `@Autowired`.

## Naming Conventions

| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Package | lowercase, module-scoped | `com.quantum.edu.auth.service` |
| Class | PascalCase | `AuthService`, `SignupRequest` |
| Method | camelCase, verb-first | `createProfile`, `findByEmail` |
| Constant | UPPER_SNAKE | `VERIFICATION_TOKEN_EXPIRY_HOURS` |
| DTO | Suffixed with Request/Response | `LoginRequest`, `AuthResponse` |
| Repository | Suffixed with Repository | `AuthUserRepository` |
| API interface | Suffixed with Api | `UserProfileApi` |

## Null Handling

- Never return `null` from service methods for collections — return empty collections.
- Use `Optional<T>` for single-entity lookups that may not exist.
- Use `@NotBlank`, `@NotNull`, `@Size` etc. on DTOs for validation — not manual null-checks in controllers.

## Immutability & Defensive Coding

- DTO fields: `private` with Lombok-generated accessors.
- Entity IDs and timestamps: mark `updatable = false` in `@Column`.
- Use `Instant` (not `Date` or `LocalDateTime`) for all timestamp fields.
- All entity PKs are `Long` with `@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)` (auto-increment).

## Method & Class Size

- Keep methods under ~30 lines. Extract private helpers for readability.
- Keep classes focused on a single responsibility.
- One public class per file.

## Comments

- Do not write comments that repeat what the code says.
- Comments are only for non-obvious intent, constraints, or trade-offs.
- Javadoc on public API interfaces that other modules consume (e.g. `UserProfileApi`).
